<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; Scotland" authorityYear="2017" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ipomoea walteri" order="Solanales" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="walteri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Ipomoea walteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is close to 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. sericophylla" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="species" species="sericophylla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">I. sericophylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but distinct because of the long-pedunculate lax inflorescence, adaxially nearly glabrous leaves and unequal sepals, the inner noticeably shorter than the outer. Particularly distinct are the strongly cuspidate leaves with a distinct apical mucro c. 3 mm long which is only matched in a few very different species, such as 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. daturiflora" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="species" species="daturiflora">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">I. daturiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Meisn.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
